VPopular artists, accompanied by noted mridangam vidwans and violinists, displayed their mastery in the vocal and other concerts.Bombay Jayashree rendered the vocal with her mellifluous voice. The kirtanas she rendered kept the audience in rapt attention all through her concert. Her &#8216;alapana&#8217; in Arabhi and Kalyani and the kirtana, &#8216;Jootha Murari&#8217; of  Tyagaraja,&#8217; &#8216;Himadri Suthe&#8217; by Syama Sastri testified to her mastery in handling the ragas. She was accompanied by Pakkala Ramadas on the violin, Poongulam Subramaniam on the mridangam and Karthick on the ghatam.Mysore Vasudha Kesav, in her &#8216;A Nati Nomu Balamo, A Dhana Palamo,&#8217; brought out the intricacies of &#8216;charanam&#8217; and &#8216;swarams.&#8217; She was accompanied by T.H.Vasantha on the violin and Salem K. Srinivasan on the mridangam.T.V.Sankaranarayanan&#8217;s concert got a good start with &#8216;Abhaya Varadhe Saradhe&#8217; in Hindolam which was followed by &#8216;Raju Vedala&#8217; in Thodi. His extensive alapana in Sankarabharanam enthralled the audience. T.K.V.Ramanujacharyulu (violin), Koviladi R. Madhvaprasad (mridangam) and Alathur T. Rajaganesh (ganjira) were at their best all through.Sowmya exhibited her special style in &#8216;Theliya Ledhu&#8217; and Swarajathi of Syama Sastrigal in Bhairavi. She was accompanied by Embar Kannan on violin and Neyveli Narayanan on the mridangam.Chinmaya Sisters, Uma and Radhika, exhibited their meticulous rendering of ragams in all their 13 rare kirtans. Balamurali, in his &#8216;Sri Sankara Guruvaram&#8217; and &#8216;Rama Neeyada&#8217; in Kharaharapriya impressed the music-lovers to a great extent.Lalgudi G.J.R.Krishnan captured the Lalgudi style in his violin concert.  He was accompanied by B. Harikumar on the mridangam and Kovai V. Mohanram on the ghatam.N. Vijay Siva, in a deft handling of 13 kirtans rendered an intelligent concert that included &#8216;Elavathara&#8217; in Mukhari, &#8216;Abhayamba&#8217; in Kalyani and &#8216;Sarada Bhujangam&#8217; of Adi Sankara glorifying Sri Sarada of Sringeri.Amrita Murali (violin) and Neyveli Narayanan (mridangam) gave cohesive support. Koviladi R. Madhwa Prasad, accompanied by T.K.V.Ramanujacharyalu on violin, Tiruchi Rangarajan on the mridangam and Alathur T. Rajaganesh on ganjira, rendered his recital. Tiruchi K. Ramesh&#8217;s main piece was in Kiravani (&#8216;Kalikiyunde&#8217;). His other interesting piece was &#8216;Sarijesi vaduka&#8217; in Thivravahini. He was accompanied by M.A.Krishnasamy on the violin, Srimushnam V. Rajarao on the mridangam and K. Murali on the ghatam.The two-hour long flute recital by N. Ramani was an amalgamation of 14 kirtanas and songs in Telugu and Tamil. Commencing with &#8216;Entharo&#8217; (Sriragam), he  exhibited his mastery in &#8216;Nagumomu&#8217; (Abheri), &#8216;Sankari Neevae&#8217; (Begada), &#8216;Raguvamsasudha&#8217; (Kadanakuduhalam), &#8216;Bhavanutha&#8217; (Mohanam), &#8216;Bhagyalakshmi&#8217; (Sri), &#8216;Theeradha Vilaiyattupillai&#8217; and &#8216;Kuarai Ondrum Illai&#8217; (both Ragamalika).Ramani was accompanied by N.C.Madhav on the violin and Srimushnam V. Rajarao on the mridangam.
